          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                In abstract algebra,
                an operation <m>*</m> on a set <m>A</m> is called a
                <em>commutative operation</em>
    <idx><h>commutative operation</h></idx>
                provided that for all <m>x, y \in A</m>, <m>x * y = y * x</m>.
                Carefully explain what it means to say that an operation <m>*</m> on a set <m>A</m> is not a commutative operation.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In abstract algebra, a <em>ring</em>
    <idx><h>ring</h></idx>
                consists of a nonempty set <m>R</m> and two operations called addition and multiplication.
                A nonzero element <m>a</m> in a ring <m>R</m> is called a <em>zero divisor</em>
    <idx><h>zero divisor</h></idx>
                provided that there exists a nonzero element <m>b</m> in <m>R</m> such that <m>ab = 0</m> or <m>ba = 0</m>.
                Carefully explain what it means to say that a nonzero element <m>a</m> in a ring <m>R</m> is not a zero divisor.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A set <m>M</m> of real numbers is called a <em>neighborhood</em>
    <idx><h>neighborhood</h></idx>
                of a real number <m>a</m> provided that there exists a positive real number
                <m>\varepsilon</m> such that the open interval
                <m>(a - \varepsilon,
                a + \varepsilon)</m> is contained in <m>M</m>.
                Carefully explain what it means to say that a set <m>M</m> is not a neighborhood of a real number <m>a</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In advanced calculus,
                a sequence of real numbers <m>\left(x_1, x_2, \ldots,
                x_k, \ldots \right)</m> is called a
                <em>Cauchy sequence</em>
    <idx><h>Cauchy sequence</h></idx>
                provided that for each positive real number <m>\varepsilon</m>,
                there exists a natural number <m>N</m> such that for all <m>m,
                n \in \N</m>,
                if <m>m > N</m> and <m>n > N</m>,
                then <m>\left| x_n - x_m \right| \lt \varepsilon</m>.
                Carefully explain what it means to say that the sequence of real numbers
                <m>\left(x_1, x_2, \ldots,
                x_k, \ldots \right)</m> is not a Cauchy sequence.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Explorations and Activities</title>
    <ol>
      <li xml:id="exer_prime">
        <p>
          <em>Prime Numbers</em>.
          The following definition of a prime number is very important in many areas of mathematics.
          We will use this definition at various places in the text.
          It is introduced now as an example of how to work with a definition in mathematics.
          <definition xml:id="D_prime">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A natural number <m>p</m> is a <term>prime number</term>
    <idx><h>prime number</h></idx>
                provided that it is greater than 1 and the only natural numbers that are factors of <m>p</m> are 1 and <m>p</m>.
                A natural number other than 1 that is not a prime number is a
                <term>composite number</term>.
    <idx><h>composite number</h></idx>
The number 1 is neither prime nor composite.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          Using the definition of a prime number,
          we see that 2, 3, 5, and 7 are prime numbers.
          Also, 4 is a composite number since
          <m>4 = 2 \cdot 2</m>; 10 is a composite number since <m>10 = 2 \cdot 5</m>;
          and 60 is a composite number since <m>60 = 4 \cdot 15</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Give examples of four natural numbers other than 2, 3, 5, and 7 that are prime numbers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain why a natural number <m>p</m> that is greater than 1 is a prime number provided that For all <m>d \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
                if <m>d</m> is a factor of <m>p</m>,
                then <m>d = 1</m> or <m>d = p</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Give examples of four natural numbers that are composite numbers and explain why they are composite numbers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write a useful description of what it means to say that a natural number is a composite number
                (other than saying that it is not prime).
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
